To create a TikZ diagram that represents the boundary string energy as a function of \( b \) for \( \frac{\pi}{4} < b < \frac{\pi}{2} \), we need to define a function and plot it over the specified range. For simplicity, let's assume the boundary string energy is given by a function \( E(b) = \sin(b) + \cos(b) \).

Here is the TikZ code to generate this plot:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{math}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
    % Define the domain and step size
    \def\xmin{0.785398} % pi/4 in radians
    \def\xmax{1.570796} % pi/2 in radians
    \def\step{0.01}

    % Draw the x-axis
    \draw[->] (-0.1, 0) -- (\xmax+0.1, 0) node[right] {$b$};

    % Draw the y-axis
    \draw[->] (0, -1.2) -- (0, 1.2) node[above] {$E(b)$};

    % Plot the function E(b) = sin(b) + cos(b)
    \foreach \x in \xmin,\step,...,\xmax {
        \pgfmathsetmacro{\y}{sin(\x r)+cos(\x r)}
        \ifnum\x=\xmin
            \coordinate (start) at (\x, \y);
        \else
            \draw[blue, thick] (start) -- (\x, \y);
            \coordinate (start) at (\x, \y);
        \fi
    }

    % Label the axes
    \node at (0, -1.3) {0};
    \node at (\xmax, 0) {\frac{\pi}{2}};
    \node at (0, 1.3) {2};
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
